snippet.textDisplay:
Felt inclined to comment when you mentioned how women get slut shamed for having sex with different men but not continuous sex with the same one. Like YES. I've been in 2 relationships, first one being 21 (now 24), and only in my last one was I sexually active (though still a little intimacy in the first). Many many firsts with him, but its odd that i'd be considered very inexperienced when for a whole year, once I felt the comfort, we we did so often, sometimes even too much. I understand that meeting different men you experience variety, but everyone's tastes and preferences will differ either way, and I learned so much about what pleases me, my body, etc. Like learning that despite being almost anti-sex up to that point due to a mixture of religious programming and insecurities, my libido was a lot higher than I expected, and I might be better off single and figure out a way to control my desire in the case of a future partner.

I'm finally starting to enjoy being single again after being heartbroken until relatively recently, and honestly part of me wishes I could have fun casual physical intimacy, but I do require that emotional connection and trust to be able to do it with someone. For better or worse. I know i'll have a lot of baggage to deal with in a future relationship based on how my sexuality has been tangled with just this one person, but tangents aside and back to main point, I just find it odd being made to feel innocent for "being with 1 guy" but having had sex more than.. I dont know, a 100 times.

snippet.textDisplay:
I am 21 as well and i have yet to get over my fear of aging and failing in life. I try to do what i want and travel but the fear that i will be 30 and a failure is so engraved in me that it makes me sad. What if i don't succeed in my field and what if i end up sticking to a job that just pays rent but doesn't fulfill me? And the perception of life basically being over after you turn 30 has affected me so much because i know in my heart it is not true and i feel like the fear of aging is basically a fear of dying which i think is a normal fear to have, but it takes away from enjoying my life since i end up always thinking where i am going to be in a couple of years and what i should be doing that i forget to think about what i should be enjoying and doing now.


p.s. reading all the comments and realizing that a lot of peoples brains are just always on overdrive makes me feel a little better about my own brain never shutting up.

On the other hand, I never really learned to be single. I was a serial monogamist and even in the year I was single and tried out polyamory I think I mostly did it to just constantly have a relationship. I don't know how to deal with it.

I also have a friend who's 30+ (and me as a young 24 yo) and I admire her independence but even she seems relationships. God life is tough. That's just it!

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm in a long-term relationship (for me at least) of almost 3 years and I often have the urge to break up with my boyfriend because I don't feel like settling down yet and have beautiful FOMO... I can't imagine that he could be the last man I have ever had a first kiss or a first touch with while I'm only 22.

I really enjoyed being single as relationships cost so much energy even though it's easy sailing. I really like my boyfriend and oftentimes I'm afraid that my feelings come from a place of uncertainty and discontent with my current situation and I'd like to change the thing that would be the easiest (but oh so hurtful) to change. I feel like, even though he doesn't expect it from me or doesn't ask for much I make decisions based on the relationship I'm in and I feel like I limit myself because I have to take care of it..

I just wish I would have met him maybe 5 years later so I could enjoy being and living just for myself a little longer.

snippet.textDisplay: I’ve always see this happen to almost everyone on valentines. And I would like to say Ladies and gents please don’t feel pressure or look down upon yourself just because you feel the need to be in a relationship especially when it comes to Valentine’s Day. I believe that Valentine’s Day is all centered around the word love. And you can express those things in many different ways. It doesn’t always have be about getting a boyfriend or girlfriend. It could be that of course but It can also be loving yourself and doing the things that you love and you’re passionate about. And if you are in a relationship don’t feel the need to plan something big for your loved one just because it’s Valentine’s Day and the media paints it like you you have to do those things. All I’m saying it’s isn’t healthy for you do self-deprecate and feel pressure on a holiday that is basically dedicated to the word love in general not anything specific. Again keep in mind the word love means multiple things not just that. Like making connections and  with friends and family as well as taking care of yourself. 💕

snippet.textDisplay:
it took getting my heartbroken by my “dream guy” to realize how clingy and codependent i was abt idealizing my partner and attaching my self worth to our relationship.

then when i finally started to feel happy being single and focusing on self love, i met my current partner... my old pattern of being clingy and codependent happened again 😭

i wondered if it meant i wasn’t “ready” and being with him was “wrong” and that i needed more time to work on myself.. it made me think we needed to break up, but being with him, i learned that i know how to be happy with myself being single, but i needed to learn how to be happy with myself while being in a relationship!

this kickstarted a newfound love for psychology and spirituality, and i learned that we unconsciously attract people who trigger these childhood wounds of not not being enough and being left behind.. not to hurt us, but to help us heal!

so if you’ve been single for a while and you meet someone you like, don’t be afraid to open yourself up to love, because we will never be completely “ready” or “whole.” love is a risk, but it is an opportunity to help us grow even more!

when you’re in a healthy, loving, and secure relationship, it helps you learn how to love yourself even more :) a relationship should never compromise/ determine your independence and self worth! 💙

p.s. i suggest following @risingwoman and @the.holistic.psychologist on instagram if you wanna learn more about this :)

snippet.textDisplay: The validation from male attention is something I've kinda realised recently. I've never been one to have a lot of guy friends, even in uni now my closest friends are girls. It really annoys me that it's somehow seen as 'better' or 'cooler' to have male friends as in saying that women aren't just as cool as guys. I feel like it definitely stems from women placing their worth in attention from men (as in cooler if you can be in a relationship with a man and that's not even mentioning how heteronormative that is!!!) as we are taught to do from an early age just like you said from romcoms etc. I feel like it has taken me until this point to realise this and to fully understand that just because I have more female friends doesn't mean I am any less or more 'cool' than if I have male ones. We shouldn't define ourselves by the gender of our friendships but instead by the quality of them. Just really interesting hearing our similar thoughts on this stuff!!

I have been in the US for 7 years now (born and raised in Morocco), and I can definitely see and feel the societal pressure everyone is taking about, however, the one thing I learned that is a big advantage people have here (in comparison to Muslim countries like Morocco) is that you have the choice to refuse that pressure.
I had a lot more pressure to get married and settle down when I was still in Morocco, but I didn’t have the choice to say no. It is such a blessing to be in a country where I can choose to not follow things I don’t believe in! We can criticize movies for all of this, but to be honest with you, if movies is where you get your standards and knowledge from, then I think you’re missing the point of movies...

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you so much for that video! I‘m 17 years old and seeing people in highschool dating and kissing in public really makes me want to have a relationship aswell. But it‘s also, as you mentioned, the romantic movies or books that make girls think that the goal is to be in love and that this is what it‘s all about. I‘ve never had a boyfriend before and I haven’t had my first kiss, and I always used to put so much pressure on myself and say that I need to have my first kiss when I‘m 15 and then it didn’t happen and then I wanted to be kissed at 16 and so on. But to be honest, who cares when I have my first kiss?! I always freaked out because like what do I tell my future boyfriend? Will he think I‘m unattractive or desperate or whatever, and what will I tell my kids later when they ask me? But really who even cares? There is no rule or no set age for a boyfriend or the first kiss - It‘ll happen when the time‘s right.
And it‘s not my life goal to be in a relationship, it‘s not what I have to do with my life.
Well, yeah, to all the other teenage girls out there, be proud of who you are and what you already achieved! You don‘t need a man to feel like a women💗
